{
  "texts": [
    "In the U.S., the doctrine of design defects necessitates assessing whether an alternative design could have averted harm caused by an AI system.",
    "However, as engineers strive to anticipate human errors that cause recurrent accidents, their design modifications might inadvertently introduce new, unexpected, and potentially more dangerous accidents stemming from the technology itself (Wendel, 2019, 379).",
    "Under EU product liability law, courts will have to judge the reasonableness of the public's inaccurate expectations of AI.",
    "A plaintiff may argue that the public may (reasonably) expect AI systems to be safer than humans 68 or that a particular 63 For instance, the legitimate safety expectations of a patient when receiving a blood transfusion, given that there is a small statistical chance of it containing a disease.",
    "See Wuyts (2014, 9) and case law referenced therein."
  ]
}